# React foundations (maintainability & extensibility)

## Core principles

- **Single responsibility**: each component, hook, and function does one thing.
- **Separate concerns**: UI (components), logic (hooks), data (services).
- Prefer readability over clever abstractions; keep code predictable and explicit.
- Components and hooks must be **pure** during render (no side effects while rendering).

## Project structure

- **Feature-based** structure, not type-based (e.g. by domain/feature, not giant `components/` / `hooks/` trees).
- Co-locate within each feature: components, hooks, services, types, and tests.
- Avoid global `utils` unless truly shared across features.
- Keep hierarchy **shallow** and intuitive.

## Clean code

- Descriptive names; functions short (<30 lines) and focused.
- Prefer early returns over deep nesting; use named constants instead of magic numbers.
- Prefer self-documenting code over noisy comments; eliminate duplication (DRY).

## Extensibility

- Prefer extension over modification; do not break existing behavior without justification.
- Design for future changes (new fields, states, APIs); keep modules loosely coupled.

## PR / change rules

- Every change follows feature-based structure.
- No large or multi-responsibility components; don’t introduce components >300 lines.
- All **new business logic** must include tests; avoid duplication.
- Code should be understandable within ~2 minutes of reading.

## Anti-patterns (reject)

- Business logic inside presentational UI; direct API calls in components.
- Components exceeding ~300 lines; deep prop drilling (prefer hooks/context).
- Overuse of `useEffect`; widespread `any`; missing tests for new logic.

## Definition of done

Readable, testable, strictly typed code; tests added and passing; no lint errors; no unjustified duplication; follows these rules.
